{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_cookie_ver02/data/sn89053307/00517177167/1908062501/0934.xml":{"full_text":"FITZGERALD ENTERPRISE\nVOLUME XIII.\nAnnual Slaughter Sale\n1 Is Now Going On At\nTHE Empire Store\nTHE GREATEST THAT HAS EVER HAPPENED\nPRICES CUT ON EVERY ARTICLE IN BOTH ROOMS.\nFITZGERALD'S\nIndustrial and Mercantile\nEnterprises to be Ex\nploited by the\nA.B. A,\nNow that the recent financial\npanic is a thing of the past, and\nconditions are resuming their nor\nmal state, enterprisee and indus\ntries are once more taking hold of\nthe reins of commerce with a firm\nhand, and where a feeling of tim\nidity prevailed only a few months\nago, this has given way to one of\nsecarity and confidence, and in the\nplace of stagnation, the polluted\nwaters of trade and finance are be\ncoming clear until today we read\nof industries all over the country\nthat are resuming operations.\nIt isa matter of history as to\nhow the A. B. &A. R. R. weath\nered the financial storm, and in\nmany instances continued the im\nprovement of the croad .in (pursu\nance with their plans. Now that\nprosperity is again sighted on the\nhorizon, they are proceeding with\ntheir plavs of improvement with\nrenewed vigor, and it is with\ngratification that the people of\nFitzgerald will learn of this move\nmenten foot to give the towna\nhigh degree of prominence.\nIt is the intention of theroad to\ncompile a Mercantile and Indus\ntrial Review of the city that will\n_not only be a credit to Fitzgerald,\nbut likewise to the road itself, and\nthe purpese of which will be to in\nfluence capitalists, manufacturers\nand laborers to establish them-\nThe edition will contain histor\nical and statistical information re\ngarding Fitzgerald, will contain\ncomparative statements regarding\nfinancial conditions, business per\nannum, increase in taxable proper\nties, increase in population, the\nper cent of death rate, the excel.\nlent climatical conditions, and in\naddition will be elaborately illus\ntrated with photographs of FKitz\ngerald\u2019s Industrial and Mercantile\nenterprises, together with scenes\nthat are indigenous to this locali\nty. Is will also state what enter\nprises there are in the city, and\nwhat euterprises the city could\nsupport should they come here,\nalso tue resources and facilities,\nboth natural and acquired that\nare to be found in Fitzgerald.\nThe cover design will be beauti\nful and attractive, representing an\nindustrial scene, and taken at it\u2019s\nbest, the edition will be one of the\nhandsomest ever gotten out by the\nroad. Messrs. Fred G. Bardwald\nand Ben S. Goldberftatisticians\nof the Traffic Department of the\nroad, have boen detailed to make\nthe compilations, and with the\nabitity of the gentlemen being\niknown, we feel sure that Fitzger\nald will be proud of the result of\ntheir work.\nNotice.\nMiss Alice Barton, a graduate of\nBessie Tift College, and a talented\nyoung lady of Ocilla, assisted by\nMrs. W. A. Puckett, of Ocilla, and\nMiss Nellie Frazier, of Fitzgerald,\nwill give a recital at the Ocilla Au\nditorium for the benefit of The\ni(}ivic Improvement League, Frid: y\nevening, June 26th, at 8 o\u2019clock.\nMrs. Puckett is asplendid pianist\nand Miss Frazier is an accomplish\ned reader.\nWe predict an evening of of rare\nentertainment for all who attend.\nAdmission 15 and 25 cents.\nT EH IRIC FEE-A W s EES\nfITZGERALD GEORGIA, THURSDAY, JUNE 25, 1908.\nCITY BONDS.\nFitzgerald did herself proud yes\nterday by almost unanimously vot\ning $75,000. for sewerage, $30,000\nfor school buildings and $25,000 for\nwater and light extension.\nThere were 405 votes register\ned, necessary for the success of the\nbond issues 270 votes.\nFor sewers 365 votes were cast\nforand 7 against,\u2018 for schools 366 for\nand 7 against.\nFor water and light extension\n369 for and 4 against. Nearly a hun\ndred votes to spare on each propos-'\nition. L\nWith these bonds Fitzgerald\nwill have about $lBO,OOO bonded in\ndebtedness leaving yet a margin of\na hundred thousand dollars on our\npresent valuation of $4,0000,000 of\ntaxable property.\u201d\nTHE STATE CONVENTION\ni Joseph M. Brown was nominat\n\u2018ed as the democratic candidate for\n\u2018governor by the state convention\n\u2018assembled in Atlanta Tuesday.\nThe convention was perhaps the\nlla.rgest; in point of numbers ever\nlassembled in the state and filled\nthe Grand Operashouse, one of the\nlargest in the South, from pit to\nI topmost gallery.\nThe utmost harmony character\nized the meeting which adopted a\n\u2018platform endorsing most of the\nimportant reforms promulgated\nby Governor sSmith\u2014notably 'chel\nTdisfranchisement of theblack voter\n\u2018and the prohibition of the liquor\ntraffic within the state. and agaiust\nthe free pass system.\nThe failure toendorse Mr. Bry\nan for the presidential nomination,\nand on the eontrary sending a\nstrong untrameled delegation to\nthe Denver convention was anoth\ner sensible things done by the\nassembled delegates, and the refus\nal to endorse the populist leader\nwho had been promiscicusly active\nin the campaign was on the same\nline.\nThe platform adopted declares\nfor \u2018\u2018Jeffersonian\u2019\u2019 democracy; for\nthe employment of idle labor at\nfair wages; for the protection of\ncapital invested and equal protect-\nWatermelon Rinds.\nThe strict enforcement ot a rule\nthat will prevent the throwing of\nwatermelon rinds promiscuously\non the streets or in alley and lots\nis important to the sanitary rcgu-\nNUMBER 83.\nion for foreign and domestic,corpqugg\n.ate and private capital; for the.\nSTRICT OONTROL AND FIRM REGU-:\nLATION OF ALL PUBLIC UTILI;,E\nCORPORATIONS leaving local corpos\nrations to the control of the muni::\ncipalities in which they are locat::\ned; a return of the county unit\nplans, lump sum payment of Con)\nfederate pensions; liberal appropri-.-\nations for common schools and thes\nprompt payment of teachem;;%\nestablishment of a department of\nlabor; the enactment of stringent\nlaws against lobbying; the bnfo;'ce\ufb01\u2018-z\nment of the prohibition lawjthe\u2019\nreduction of the state\u2019s payroll, es:\"\npecially as to the raiiroad commigs::\nsion; a white primary open to all\nwhite voters obligating themselves:;\nto support the nominees in apnfg\nmary not to be held earlier than::\nAugust and not to be held until\u00ae\nafter the adjournment of the leg-\nislature; against undesirable imnyi\ngration; in favor or thesuffragelaw\nto be radified at the next October\nelection; to changes in the wp%i\nsystem so as to eliminate traffig:in.\nconvict labor, and as far as pomi{f\u2019\"\nble place the state\u2019s convicts upel:\npublic works; to the re-establi shi:\nment of confidence and last but net:\nleast to the restoration of\nity. e\nulations of the city, some system\nis necessary for the daily removal\nof the rinds. The barrels once pro\nvided for trash have rusted out and\nthe public is at a loss to know\nwhat to do, Dr. Osborne it is up\nto you. There is no time m\ufb01\nlost on formalties.","height":"28645","width":"20512"}}
